{"title_page": "Jolene Anderson", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian actress and singer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Jolene Anderson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|05|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Kempsey, New South Wales|Kempsey]], [[New South Wales, Australia]]\n| occupation = Actress, singer\n}}\n\n'''Jolene Anderson''' (born 26 May 1980 in [[Kempsey, New South Wales]]) is an Australian actress and singer. In 2014, she joined the cast of ''[[Home and Away]]'' as newcomer [[List of Home and Away characters (2014)#Neive Devlin|Neive Devlin]].\n\nFrom 2006 to 2008 she played the character of [[Erica Templeton]] on the drama series ''[[All Saints (TV series)|All Saints]]''. She is also the winner of the second series of celebrity singing competition ''[[It Takes Two (Australian TV series)|It Takes Two]]''.\n\nIn 2019 she joined the cast of ''[[Harrow (TV series)|Harrow]]'' for Season 2 as Dr. Grace Molyneux.\n\n==Career==\n===Television===\nAnderson played Erica Templeton on ''All Saints'' until 18 November 2008, when her character was pronounced dead, as she had been missing for 3 weeks. She was one of the younger cast members and reputedly popular with the audience.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nIn the first episode of the 2007 season of ''[[It Takes Two (Australian TV series)|It Takes Two]]'', Anderson and her partner [[David Campbell (Australian musician)|David Campbell]] performed \"[[The Sweet Escape (song)|The Sweet Escape]]\" by [[Gwen Stefani]] and scored eights from all four judges giving them a score of 32 and therefore being at the top of the leaderboard for the first episode of the series. She continued to score highly amongst the judges and was one of the favourites for the entire competition.  On 19 June 2007, she became the first contestant in the show to score a perfect ten from all four judges on both performances. Anderson and Campbell went on to win ''It Takes Two'' on 10 July 2007.\n\nAnderson later accepted the role of \"Our Girl\" in the [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] song cycle ''[[Tell Me on a Sunday]]''. The production had mixed reviews, but Jolene's performance was generally well received, in her musical theatre debut.<ref>http://www.thewest.com.au/aapstory.aspx?StoryName=506666 {{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/news/local/news/general/jolenes-a-onewoman-show/1229669.aspx Jolene's a one-woman show], BY JODIE MINUS, 30 Jul, 2008, Illawarra Mercury:</ref>\n\nAnderson hosted ''[[Bush Doctors]]'' in 2008, introducing and doing voice-overs during the show. The series aired from January to March 2008.\n\nAnderson signed on to become a series regular in the [[Ten Network]] cop drama series ''[[Rush (2008 TV series)|Rush]]''. Her character, Shannon Henry, made her debut in the series' second season which premiered on 16 July 2009.\n\nIn 2019 Anderson joined the cast of ''[[Harrow (TV series)|Harrow]]'' playing Dr. Grace Molyneux, a junior medical examiner with a mysterious past and Harrow's love interest for Season 2.\n\n===Theatre===\nFrom 14 November 2011 to 10 December 2011, Anderson was cast as the leading role of Hypatia, in [[Queensland Theatre Company]]'s Fractions, by Marcel Dorney.<ref name=\"Fractions\">[http://www.queenslandtheatre.com.au/plays/whats-on/2011-season/main-season/queensland-premiers-drama-award Fractions], Queensland Theatre Company</ref> Hypatia is a brilliant female mathematician and philosopher who, 1600 years ago, was responsible for the Library of Alexandria - a collection of all the knowledge in her world. When political turmoil runs unchecked, religious fanatics threaten to destroy the Library. As Hypatia struggles to save it, she is forced to confront her own prejudice, and to make a terrible choice.<ref name=\"Fractions\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Adieu'' || Gloria || Short film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Game'' || Olivia || Short film\n|-\n| 2013 || ''Beyond Memories'' || Sophie || Short film\n|-\n| 2017 || ''Living Space'' || Officer's wife || feature film\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Prey (2019 American film)|Prey]]'' || Mother || feature film\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2006\u20132008 || ''[[All Saints (TV series)|All Saints]]'' || Erica Templeton || 106 episodes\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Bush Doctors]]'' || Host ||\n|-\n| 2009\u20132012 || ''[[Play School (Australian TV series)|Play School]]'' || Host ||\n|-\n| 2009\u20132011 || ''[[Rush (2008 TV series)|Rush]]'' || Sergeant Shannon Henry || 57 episodes\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Dance Academy]]'' || April || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015 || ''[[Home and Away]]'' || [[List of Home and Away characters (2014)#Neive Devlin|Neive Devlin]] || 15 episodes\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Harrow (TV series)|Harrow]]'' || Dr. Grace Molyneux || 10 episodes\n|}\n\n=== Video Games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Titanfall 2]]''\n|Sarah Briggs\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Resident Evil 2 (2019 video game)]]\n|Ada Wong\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Life Is Strange 2]]\n|Karen Reynolds\n|\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n\nAnderson has been nominated for a [[Logie Award]] in 2007 for Most Popular New Female Talent for her role as Erica Templeton in ''[[All Saints (TV series)|All Saints]]'' but lost out to [[Amy Mathews]] from ''[[Home and Away]]''.\n\nIn 2020, Anderson was nomination for a [[British Academy Games Award for Performer|British Academy Games Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role]] at the [[16th British Academy Games Awards|16th BAFTA Games Awards]] for her role as Karen Reynolds in ''[[Life Is Strange 2]]''.<ref>http://www.bafta.org/games/awards/bafta-games-awards-nominations-and-winners-2020#performer-in-a-supporting-role</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|2279579}}\n* [archive.org/web/20060615163216/https://web.archive.org/web/20060615163216/http://au.yahoo.com/it-takes-two/ It Takes Two official website] \n* [http://au.blogs.yahoo.com/all-saints/ All Saints official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Jolene}}\n[[Category:Australian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian female singers]]\n[[Category:Singing talent show winners]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:People from the Mid North Coast]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Children's television presenters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian actress and singer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Jolene Anderson\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1980|05|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Kempsey, New South Wales|Kempsey]], [[New South Wales, Australia]]\n| occupation = Actress, singer\n}}\n\n'''Jolene Anderson''' (born 26 May 1980 in [[Kempsey, New South Wales]]) is an Australian actress and singer. In 2014, she joined the cast of ''[[Home and Away]]'' as newcomer [[List of Home and Away characters (2014)#Neive Devlin|Neive Devlin]].\n\nFrom 2006 to 2008 she played the character of [[Erica Templeton]] on the drama series ''[[All Saints (TV series)|All Saints]]''. She is also the winner of the second series of celebrity singing competition ''[[It Takes Two (Australian TV series)|It Takes Two]]''.\n\nIn 2019 she joined the cast of ''[[Harrow (TV series)|Harrow]]'' for Season 2 as Dr. Grace Molyneux.\n\n==Career==\n===Television===\nAnderson played Erica Templeton on ''All Saints'' until 18 November 2008, when her character was pronounced dead, as she had been missing for 3 weeks. She was one of the younger cast members and reputedly popular with the audience.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}}\n\nIn the first episode of the 2007 season of ''[[It Takes Two (Australian TV series)|It Takes Two]]'', Anderson and her partner [[David Campbell (Australian musician)|David Campbell]] performed \"[[The Sweet Escape (song)|The Sweet Escape]]\" by [[Gwen Stefani]] and scored eights from all four judges giving them a score of 32 and therefore being at the top of the leaderboard for the first episode of the series. She continued to score highly amongst the judges and was one of the favourites for the entire competition.  On 19 June 2007, she became the first contestant in the show to score a perfect ten from all four judges on both performances. Anderson and Campbell went on to win ''It Takes Two'' on 10 July 2007.\n\nAnderson later accepted the role of \"Our Girl\" in the [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] song cycle ''[[Tell Me on a Sunday]]''. The production had mixed reviews, but Jolene's performance was generally well received, in her musical theatre debut.<ref>http://www.thewest.com.au/aapstory.aspx?StoryName=506666 {{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/news/local/news/general/jolenes-a-onewoman-show/1229669.aspx Jolene's a one-woman show], BY JODIE MINUS, 30 Jul, 2008, Illawarra Mercury:</ref>\n\nAnderson hosted ''[[Bush Doctors]]'' in 2008, introducing and doing voice-overs during the show. The series aired from January to March 2008.\n\nAnderson signed on to become a series regular in the [[Ten Network]] cop drama series ''[[Rush (2008 TV series)|Rush]]''. Her character, Shannon Henry, made her debut in the series' second season which premiered on 16 July 2009.\n\nIn 2019 Anderson joined the cast of ''[[Harrow (TV series)|Harrow]]'' playing Dr. Grace Molyneux, a junior medical examiner with a mysterious past and Harrow's love interest for Season 2.\n\n===Theatre===\nFrom 14 November 2011 to 10 December 2011, Anderson was cast as the leading role of Hypatia, in [[Queensland Theatre Company]]'s Fractions, by Marcel Dorney.<ref name=\"Fractions\">[http://www.queenslandtheatre.com.au/plays/whats-on/2011-season/main-season/queensland-premiers-drama-award Fractions], Queensland Theatre Company</ref> Hypatia is a brilliant female mathematician and philosopher who, 1600 years ago, was responsible for the Library of Alexandria - a collection of all the knowledge in her world. When political turmoil runs unchecked, religious fanatics threaten to destroy the Library. As Hypatia struggles to save it, she is forced to confront her own prejudice, and to make a terrible choice.<ref name=\"Fractions\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Adieu'' || Gloria || Short film\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Game'' || Olivia || Short film\n|-\n| 2013 || ''Beyond Memories'' || Sophie || Short film\n|-\n| 2017 || ''Living Space'' || Officer's wife || feature film\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Prey (2019 film)|Prey]]'' || Mother || feature film\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2006\u20132008 || ''[[All Saints (TV series)|All Saints]]'' || Erica Templeton || 106 episodes\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Bush Doctors]]'' || Host ||\n|-\n| 2009\u20132012 || ''[[Play School (Australian TV series)|Play School]]'' || Host ||\n|-\n| 2009\u20132011 || ''[[Rush (2008 TV series)|Rush]]'' || Sergeant Shannon Henry || 57 episodes\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Dance Academy]]'' || April || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015 || ''[[Home and Away]]'' || [[List of Home and Away characters (2014)#Neive Devlin|Neive Devlin]] || 15 episodes\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Harrow (TV series)|Harrow]]'' || Dr. Grace Molyneux || 10 episodes\n|}\n\n=== Video Games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Titanfall 2]]''\n|Sarah Briggs\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Resident Evil 2 (2019 video game)]]\n|Ada Wong\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Life Is Strange 2]]\n|Karen Reynolds\n|\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n\nAnderson has been nominated for a [[Logie Award]] in 2007 for Most Popular New Female Talent for her role as Erica Templeton in ''[[All Saints (TV series)|All Saints]]'' but lost out to [[Amy Mathews]] from ''[[Home and Away]]''.\n\nIn 2020, Anderson was nomination for a [[British Academy Games Award for Performer|British Academy Games Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role]] at the [[16th British Academy Games Awards|16th BAFTA Games Awards]] for her role as Karen Reynolds in ''[[Life Is Strange 2]]''.<ref>http://www.bafta.org/games/awards/bafta-games-awards-nominations-and-winners-2020#performer-in-a-supporting-role</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|2279579}}\n* [archive.org/web/20060615163216/https://web.archive.org/web/20060615163216/http://au.yahoo.com/it-takes-two/ It Takes Two official website] \n* [http://au.blogs.yahoo.com/all-saints/ All Saints official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Jolene}}\n[[Category:Australian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian female singers]]\n[[Category:Singing talent show winners]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:People from the Mid North Coast]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Children's television presenters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]