{"title_page": "Michael Rummenigge", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Michael Rummenigge\n| image          = 2011-12-30 Bonn Telekom-Dome Michael Rummenigge.jpg\n| caption        = Rummenigge playing for a [[Borussia Dortmund]] veterans team in 2011\n| fullname       = Michael Rummenigge\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1964|2|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lippstadt]], [[West Germany]]\n| height         = 1.74 m\n| currentclub    =\n| position       = [[Midfielder]], [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]]\n| youthyears1    = 1970\u20131981\n| youthclubs1    = [[Borussia Lippstadt]]\n| youthyears2    = 1981\u20131982\n| youthclubs2    = [[Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]]\n| years1         = 1982\u20131988\n| clubs1         = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n| caps1          = 152\n| goals1         = 44\n| years2         = 1988\u20131993\n| clubs2         = [[Borussia Dortmund]]\n| caps2          = 157\n| goals2         = 36\n| years3         = 1993\u20131995\n| clubs3         = [[Urawa Reds]]\n| caps3          = 42\n| goals3         = 13\n| totalcaps      = 351\n| totalgoals     = 93\n| nationalyears1 = 1980\u20131982\n| nationalteam1  = [[Germany national under-18 football team|West Germany U-18]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 1983\u20131985\n| nationalteam2  = [[Germany national under-21 football team|West Germany U-21]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 10\n| nationalgoals2 = 4\n| nationalyears3 = 1983\u20131986\n| nationalteam3  = [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{medalTeam|[[Bayern Munich]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Pokal]]|[[1983\u201384 DFB-Pokal|1984]]}}\n{{medalW|[[Bundesliga]]|[[1984\u201385 Bundesliga|1985]]}}\n{{medalRU|[[DFB-Pokal]]|[[1984\u201385 DFB-Pokal|1985]]}}\n{{medalW|[[Bundesliga]]|[[1985\u201386 Bundesliga|1986]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Pokal]]|[[1985\u201386 DFB-Pokal|1986]]}}\n{{medalW|[[Bundesliga]]|[[1986\u201387 Bundesliga|1987]]}}\n{{medalRU|[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]|[[1986\u201387 European Cup|1987]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Supercup]]|[[1987 DFB-Supercup|1987]]}}\n{{medalTeam|[[Borussia Dortmund]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Pokal]]|[[1988\u201389 DFB-Pokal|1989]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Supercup]]|[[1989 DFB-Supercup|1989]]}}\n{{medalRU|[[UEFA Cup]]|[[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup|1993]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Rummenigge''' (born 3 February 1964) is a German former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2006-07/borussia-dortmund-17/12574/spieler_michael-rummenigge.html | title = Rummenigge, Michael | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 5 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRummenigge was born in [[Lippstadt]], North Rhine-Westphalia. At the beginning of his career, he did not have it easy as a player with the Bayern Munich star team. He was often compared to his older brother, [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]], captain of FC Bayern Munich and the German national team. Rummenigge joined Bayern Munich in 1981 as a member of the German junior national team at the age of 17, coming from Borussia Lippstadt. His brother, Karl-Heinz, was already an international top star player. Rummenigge became a professional player in Munich in 1982 and a starter in his second season in 1983. He played for Bayern Munich till 1988. By that time his team had won the German championship three times and the DFB-Pokal two times (in 1984 and 1986).\n\nDuring his career, Rummenigge was capped twice for the German national team and represented Germany on two occasions in 1983 and 1986.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://rsssf.com/miscellaneous/mrummenigge-intl.html | title = Michael Rummenigge - International Appearances | first = Matthias | last = Arnhold | date = 13 September 2018 | accessdate = 25 September 2018 | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, he changed team affiliation to Borussia Dortmund. In spite of not being very popular with Borussia's supporters in the beginning, he won the DFB-Pokal with Dortmund by the end of his first season \u2013 the first title for Borussia Dortmund since the 1960s. Borussia Dortmund defeated Werder Bremen 4\u20131 in [[Berlin, Germany|Berlin]].\n\nIn 1991\u201392, after the arrival of the new BVB coach, [[Ottmar Hitzfeld]], he was appointed captain of the team. In the same year, Borussia Dortmund became the runner-up in the German championship. In 1993, he played in the UEFA Cup final for Borussia Dortmund against Juventus. Dortmund lost 6\u20131 on aggregate with Rummenigge scoring their only goal.\n\nRummenigge finished his career in the black and yellow football shirt of Dortmund in 1993. After having played 309 times in the [[Bundesliga]] and having scored 80 goals,<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://rsssf.com/players/mrummeniggedata.html | title = Michael Rummenigge - Matches and Goals in Bundesliga | first = Matthias | last = Arnhold | date = 13 September 2018 | accessdate = 25 September 2018 | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]}}</ref> he moved on to Japan where a professional football league had just been launched. He played for Urawa Red Diamonds, Japan till 1995. At the beginning of 1996 he had to give up his career because of a severe toe injury.\n\n==Business==\nRummenigge is a trained banker and runs a successful sports marketing agency in Dortmund (Sports & Business) as well as commercial football camps (Fu\u00dfballschule Michael Rummenigge). In addition he is a partner/shareholder of the Sportnex GmbH in Munich.\n\nHe is also a partner of \"Germany's best indoor soccer courts\"<ref>\"Beste Soccer-Halle Deutschlands\". Bolzen-Magazin & 11 Freunde, 2006 and 2007</ref> in M\u00fcnster and launched (together with a different partner) another new business, \"Trendsport Rummenigge\", which distributes mobile soccer courts, cages and playing fields.\n\nRummenigge also shows a remarkable social commitment. He works as patron for the initiative \"NO DRUGS\" \u2013 an initiative against drug abuse and also for the association Childrensmile e. V. which supports severely ill and disadvantaged children.\n\nIn June 2007, he passed his exam to be a professional football coach with distinction (UEFA Pro licence) at the German sport university in Cologne.\n\n==Personal life==\nRummenigge is married to Carolin and has three sons.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref>{{NFT|16945|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season\n! Club\n! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n! colspan=3 |Germany\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[DFB-Pokal]]\n! colspan=2 | [[DFB Ligapokal]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|1982\u201383||rowspan=\"6\"|[[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Bundesliga]]||1||0||||||||||1||0\n|-\n|1983\u201384||33||11||||||||||33||11\n|-\n|1984\u201385||24||5||||||||||24||5\n|-\n|1985\u201386||31||10||||||||||31||10\n|-\n|1986\u201387||31||8||||||||||31||8\n|-\n|1987\u201388||32||10||||||||||32||10\n|-\n|1988\u201389||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Borussia Dortmund]]||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Bundesliga]]||32||4||||||||||32||4\n|-\n|1989\u201390||29||9||||||||||29||9\n|-\n|1990\u201391||31||8||||||||||31||8\n|-\n|1991\u201392||36||10||||||||||36||10\n|-\n|1992\u201393||26||4||||||||||26||4\n|-\n|1993\u201394||3||1||||||||||3||1\n|-\n! colspan=3 |Japan\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Emperor's Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[J.League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[1993 Urawa Red Diamonds season|1993]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Urawa Reds]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[J1 League]]||6||1||2||0||3||3||11||4\n|-\n|[[1994 Urawa Red Diamonds season|1994]]||27||11||0||0||2||1||29||12\n|-\n|[[1995 Urawa Red Diamonds season|1995]]||9||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|-||9||1\n|-\n!rowspan=2| Country !!colspan=2| Germany\n!309||80||||||||||309||80\n|-\n!colspan=2|Japan\n!42||13||2||0||5||4||49||17\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n!351||93||2||0||5||4||358||97\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1983||1||0\n|-\n|1984||0||0\n|-\n|1985||0||0\n|-\n|1986||1||0\n|-\n!Total||2||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Bayern Munich'''\n* [[Bundesliga]]: [[1984\u201385 Bundesliga|1984\u201385]], [[1985\u201386 Bundesliga|1985\u201386]], [[1986\u201387 Bundesliga|1986\u201387]]\n* [[DFB-Pokal]]: [[1983\u201384 DFB-Pokal|1983\u201384]], [[1985\u201386 DFB-Pokal|1985\u201386]]\n* [[DFL-Supercup]]: [[1987 DFB-Supercup|1987]]\n* [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]: Runner-up [[1986\u201387 European Cup|1986\u201387]]\n\n'''Borussia Dortmund'''\n* [[DFB-Pokal]]: [[1988\u201389 DFB-Pokal|1988\u201389]]\n* [[DFL-Supercup]]: [[1989 DFB-Supercup|1989]]\n* [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: Runner-up [[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup|1992\u201393]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Worldfootball.net|michael-rummenigge}}\n* {{Fussballdaten|michael-rummenigge}}\n* {{NFT|16945}}\n* {{J.League player}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rummenigge, Michael}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lippstadt]]\n[[Category:German expatriate sportspeople in Japan]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:German expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:FC Bayern Munich footballers]]\n[[Category:Borussia Dortmund players]]\n[[Category:Urawa Red Diamonds players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Japan]]\n[[Category:J1 League players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Michael Rummenigge\n| image          = 2011-12-30 Bonn Telekom-Dome Michael Rummenigge.jpg\n| caption        = Rummenigge playing for a [[Borussia Dortmund]] veterans team in 2011\n| fullname       = Michael Rummenigge\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1964|2|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lippstadt]], [[West Germany]]\n| height         = 1.74 m\n| currentclub    =\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]/[[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| youthyears1    = 1970\u20131981\n| youthclubs1    = [[Borussia Lippstadt]]\n| youthyears2    = 1981\u20131982\n| youthclubs2    = [[Bayern Munich Junior Team|Bayern Munich]]\n| years1         = 1982\u20131988\n| clubs1         = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n| caps1          = 152\n| goals1         = 44\n| years2         = 1988\u20131993\n| clubs2         = [[Borussia Dortmund]]\n| caps2          = 157\n| goals2         = 36\n| years3         = 1993\u20131995\n| clubs3         = [[Urawa Reds]]\n| caps3          = 42\n| goals3         = 13\n| totalcaps      = 351\n| totalgoals     = 93\n| nationalyears1 = 1980\u20131982\n| nationalteam1  = [[Germany national under-18 football team|West Germany U-18]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 1983\u20131985\n| nationalteam2  = [[Germany national under-21 football team|West Germany U-21]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 10\n| nationalgoals2 = 4\n| nationalyears3 = 1983\u20131986\n| nationalteam3  = [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{medalTeam|[[Bayern Munich]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Pokal]]|[[1983\u201384 DFB-Pokal|1984]]}}\n{{medalW|[[Bundesliga]]|[[1984\u201385 Bundesliga|1985]]}}\n{{medalRU|[[DFB-Pokal]]|[[1984\u201385 DFB-Pokal|1985]]}}\n{{medalW|[[Bundesliga]]|[[1985\u201386 Bundesliga|1986]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Pokal]]|[[1985\u201386 DFB-Pokal|1986]]}}\n{{medalW|[[Bundesliga]]|[[1986\u201387 Bundesliga|1987]]}}\n{{medalRU|[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]|[[1986\u201387 European Cup|1987]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Supercup]]|[[1987 DFB-Supercup|1987]]}}\n{{medalTeam|[[Borussia Dortmund]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Pokal]]|[[1988\u201389 DFB-Pokal|1989]]}}\n{{medalW|[[DFB-Supercup]]|[[1989 DFB-Supercup|1989]]}}\n{{medalRU|[[UEFA Cup]]|[[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup|1993]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Rummenigge''' (born 3 February 1964 in [[Lippstadt]], North Rhine-Westphalia) is a German former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2006-07/borussia-dortmund-17/12574/spieler_michael-rummenigge.html | title = Rummenigge, Michael | language = German | publisher = kicker.de | accessdate = 5 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt the beginning of his career, Rummenigge did not have it easy as a player with the Bayern Munich star team. He was often compared to his older brother, [[Karl-Heinz Rummenigge]], captain of FC Bayern Munich and the German national team. Rummenigge joined Bayern Munich in 1981 as a member of the German junior national team at the age of 17, coming from Borussia Lippstadt. His brother, Karl-Heinz, was already an international top star player. Rummenigge became a professional player in Munich in 1982 and a starter in his second season in 1983. He played for Bayern Munich till 1988. By that time his team had won the German championship three times and the DFB-Pokal two times (in 1984 and 1986).\n\nDuring his career, Rummenigge was capped twice for the German national team and represented Germany on two occasions in 1983 and 1986.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://rsssf.com/miscellaneous/mrummenigge-intl.html | title = Michael Rummenigge - International Appearances | first = Matthias | last = Arnhold | date = 13 September 2018 | accessdate = 25 September 2018 | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, he changed team affiliation to Borussia Dortmund. In spite of not being very popular with Borussia's supporters in the beginning, he won the DFB-Pokal with Dortmund by the end of his first season \u2013 the first title for Borussia Dortmund since the 1960s. Borussia Dortmund defeated Werder Bremen 4\u20131 in [[Berlin, Germany|Berlin]].\n\nIn 1991\u201392, after the arrival of the new BVB coach, [[Ottmar Hitzfeld]], he was appointed captain of the team. In the same year, Borussia Dortmund became the runner-up in the German championship. In 1993, he played in the UEFA Cup final for Borussia Dortmund against Juventus. Dortmund lost 6\u20131 on aggregate with Rummenigge scoring their only goal.\n\nRummenigge finished his career in the black and yellow football shirt of Dortmund in 1993. After having played 309 times in the [[Bundesliga]] and having scored 80 goals,<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://rsssf.com/players/mrummeniggedata.html | title = Michael Rummenigge - Matches and Goals in Bundesliga | first = Matthias | last = Arnhold | date = 13 September 2018 | accessdate = 25 September 2018 | publisher = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]}}</ref> he moved on to Japan where a professional football league had just been launched. He played for Urawa Red Diamonds, Japan till 1995. At the beginning of 1996 he had to give up his career because of a severe toe injury.\n\n==Business==\nRummenigge is a trained banker and runs a successful sports marketing agency in Dortmund (Sports & Business) as well as commercial football camps (Fu\u00dfballschule Michael Rummenigge). In addition he is a partner/shareholder of the Sportnex GmbH in Munich.\n\nHe is also a partner of \"Germany's best indoor soccer courts\"<ref>\"Beste Soccer-Halle Deutschlands\". Bolzen-Magazin & 11 Freunde, 2006 and 2007</ref> in M\u00fcnster and launched (together with a different partner) another new business, \"Trendsport Rummenigge\", which distributes mobile soccer courts, cages and playing fields.\n\nRummenigge also shows a remarkable social commitment. He works as patron for the initiative \"NO DRUGS\" \u2013 an initiative against drug abuse and also for the association Childrensmile e. V. which supports severely ill and disadvantaged children.\n\nIn June 2007, he passed his exam to be a professional football coach with distinction (UEFA Pro licence) at the German sport university in Cologne.\n\n==Personal life==\nRummenigge is married to Carolin and has three sons.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n<ref>{{NFT player|id=16945|accessdate=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season\n! Club\n! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n! colspan=3 |Germany\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[DFB-Pokal]]\n! colspan=2 | [[DFB Ligapokal]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|1982\u201383||rowspan=\"6\"|[[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Bundesliga]]||1||0||||||||||1||0\n|-\n|1983\u201384||33||11||||||||||33||11\n|-\n|1984\u201385||24||5||||||||||24||5\n|-\n|1985\u201386||31||10||||||||||31||10\n|-\n|1986\u201387||31||8||||||||||31||8\n|-\n|1987\u201388||32||10||||||||||32||10\n|-\n|1988\u201389||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Borussia Dortmund]]||rowspan=\"6\"|[[Bundesliga]]||32||4||||||||||32||4\n|-\n|1989\u201390||29||9||||||||||29||9\n|-\n|1990\u201391||31||8||||||||||31||8\n|-\n|1991\u201392||36||10||||||||||36||10\n|-\n|1992\u201393||26||4||||||||||26||4\n|-\n|1993\u201394||3||1||||||||||3||1\n|-\n! colspan=3 |Japan\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Emperor's Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[J.League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[1993 Urawa Red Diamonds season|1993]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Urawa Reds]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[J1 League]]||6||1||2||0||3||3||11||4\n|-\n|[[1994 Urawa Red Diamonds season|1994]]||27||11||0||0||2||1||29||12\n|-\n|[[1995 Urawa Red Diamonds season|1995]]||9||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|-||9||1\n|-\n!rowspan=2| Country !!colspan=2| Germany\n!309||80||||||||||309||80\n|-\n!colspan=2|Japan\n!42||13||2||0||5||4||49||17\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n!351||93||2||0||5||4||358||97\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1983||1||0\n|-\n|1984||0||0\n|-\n|1985||0||0\n|-\n|1986||1||0\n|-\n!Total||2||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Bayern Munich'''\n* [[Bundesliga]]: [[1984\u201385 Bundesliga|1984\u201385]], [[1985\u201386 Bundesliga|1985\u201386]], [[1986\u201387 Bundesliga|1986\u201387]]\n* [[DFB-Pokal]]: [[1983\u201384 DFB-Pokal|1983\u201384]], [[1985\u201386 DFB-Pokal|1985\u201386]]\n* [[DFL-Supercup]]: [[1987 DFB-Supercup|1987]]\n* [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]: Runner-up [[1986\u201387 European Cup|1986\u201387]]\n\n'''Borussia Dortmund'''\n* [[DFB-Pokal]]: [[1988\u201389 DFB-Pokal|1988\u201389]]\n* [[DFL-Supercup]]: [[1989 DFB-Supercup|1989]]\n* [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: Runner-up [[1992\u201393 UEFA Cup|1992\u201393]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Worldfootball.net|michael-rummenigge}}\n* {{Fussballdaten|id=michael-rummenigge}}\n* {{NFT player|pid=16945}}\n* {{J.League player}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rummenigge, Michael}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lippstadt]]\n[[Category:German expatriate sportspeople in Japan]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:German expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany international footballers]]\n[[Category:Germany under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:FC Bayern Munich footballers]]\n[[Category:Borussia Dortmund players]]\n[[Category:Urawa Red Diamonds players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Japan]]\n[[Category:J1 League players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Move content relating to his personal life to a dedicated section.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Rummenigge"}
{"title_page": "Beverley to Perth Cycle Race", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe '''Beverley to Perth Cycle Race''' (also known as ''The Beverley'') is a road bicycle race conducted between [[Beverley, Western Australia|Beverley]] and [[Perth]] in [[Western Australia]].  In early years it had also been known as '''Armstrong's Road Race'''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article67031517 |title=CYCLING. |newspaper=[[The Inquirer And Commercial News]] |location=Western Australia |date=23 September 1898 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nIt was run in conjunction with the '''League of W.A. Wheelmen''',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article33218406 |title=CYCLING. |newspaper=[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]] |location=Western Australia |date=28 September 1901 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=57 |via=Trove }}</ref> and had had vice-regal patronage with the Governor of Western Australia's participation as judge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article67031517 |title=CYCLING. |newspaper=[[The Inquirer And Commercial News]] |location=Western Australia |date=23 September 1898 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nIt was established in 1897. There were no races in 1900, 1902, or during the first world war.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article256991286 |title=Beverley to Perth. |newspaper=[[The Magpie and Australian]] |location=Western Australia |date=28 September 1923 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=8 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nThe race was established by Percy W. Armstrong,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article251507634 |title=The Late P. W . Armstrong. |newspaper=[[Midlands Advocate]] |location=Western Australia |date=18 September 1942 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> who in 1937, protested the change of the route in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41434345 |title=BEVERLEY-PERTH CYCLE RACE. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Western Australia |date=28 September 1937 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=9 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nI even reversed direction of the running of the race in 1952.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article252531762 |title=The Beverley to Perth |newspaper=[[York Chronicle]] |location=Western Australia |date=10 July 1952 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=3 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nThe race continued regularly after the second world war,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article252536305 |title=THE BEVERLEY TO PERTH |newspaper=[[York Chronicle]] |location=Western Australia |date=24 September 1953 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=1 |via=Trove }}</ref>   and into the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article201783056 |title=Cyclist wins Beverley-to-Perth for the second time |newspaper=[[The Beverley Times]] |location=Western Australia |date=20 September 1973 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=1 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nThe race suspended in 1999, and involved a ''return'' in 2016.<ref>https://westcycle.org.au/the-beverley-a-classic-race-returns/The Beverley a classic race returns</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Cycle races in Australia]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1897]]\n[[Category:1897 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Men's road bicycle races]]\n[[Category:Women's road bicycle races]]\n[[Category:Annual sporting events in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Western Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe '''Beverley to Perth Cycle Race''' (also known as ''The Beverley'') is a road bicycle race conducted between [[Beverley, Western Australia|Beverley]] and [[Perth]] in [[Western Australia]].  In early years it had also been known as '''Armstrong's Road Race'''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article67031517 |title=CYCLING. |newspaper=[[The Inquirer And Commercial News]] |location=Western Australia |date=23 September 1898 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nIt was run in conjunction with the '''League of W.A. Wheelmen''',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article33218406 |title=CYCLING. |newspaper=[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]] |location=Western Australia |date=28 September 1901 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=57 |via=Trove }}</ref> and had had vice-regal patronage with the Governor of Western Australia's participation as judge.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article67031517 |title=CYCLING. |newspaper=[[The Inquirer And Commercial News]] |location=Western Australia |date=23 September 1898 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nIt was established in 1897. There were no races in 1900, 1902, or during the first world war.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article256991286 |title=Beverley to Perth. |newspaper=[[The Magpie and Australian]] |location=Western Australia |date=28 September 1923 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=8 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nThe race was established by P.W. Armstrong,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article251507634 |title=The Late P. W . Armstrong. |newspaper=[[Midlands Advocate]] |location=Western Australia |date=18 September 1942 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> who in 1937, protested the change of the route in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article41434345 |title=BEVERLEY-PERTH CYCLE RACE. |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Western Australia |date=28 September 1937 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=9 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nI even reversed direction of the running of the race in 1952.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article252531762 |title=The Beverley to Perth |newspaper=[[York Chronicle]] |location=Western Australia |date=10 July 1952 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=3 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nThe race continued regularly after the second world war,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article252536305 |title=THE BEVERLEY TO PERTH |newspaper=[[York Chronicle]] |location=Western Australia |date=24 September 1953 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=1 |via=Trove }}</ref>   and into the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article201783056 |title=Cyclist wins Beverley-to-Perth for the second time |newspaper=[[The Beverley Times]] |location=Western Australia |date=20 September 1973 |access-date=10 February 2020 |page=1 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nThe race suspended in 1999, and involved a ''return'' in 2016.<ref>https://westcycle.org.au/the-beverley-a-classic-race-returns/The Beverley a classic race returns</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Cycle races in Australia]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1897]]\n[[Category:1897 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Men's road bicycle races]]\n[[Category:Women's road bicycle races]]\n[[Category:Annual sporting events in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Western Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Frithnow", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Percy Armstrong's given name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beverley_to_Perth_Cycle_Race"}
{"title_page": "Rail (bird)", "text_new": "{{short description|Family of birds}}\n{{automatic taxobox\n| name = Rails\n| fossil_range = {{geo range|Early Eocene|recent}}\n| image = Dusky moorhen442.jpg\n| image_caption = [[Dusky moorhen]], ''Gallinula tenebrosa''\n| taxon = Rallidae\n| authority = [[Constantine Samuel Rafinesque|Rafinesque]], 1815\n| subdivision_ranks = Genera\n| subdivision = Some 40 living, and see [[#Systematics and evolution|below]].\n}}\n\nThe '''rails''', or '''Rallidae''', are a large [[Cosmopolitan distribution|cosmopolitan]] [[family (biology)|family]] of small- to medium-sized, ground-living [[bird]]s. The family exhibits considerable [[Biodiversity|diversity]] and includes the '''crakes''', '''coots''', and '''gallinules'''. Many [[species]] are associated with [[wetland]]s, although the family is found in every [[Terrestrial animal|terrestrial]] [[habitat]] except dry [[desert]]s, [[Polar climate|polar]] regions, and [[Alpine climate|alpine]] areas above the [[snow line]]. Members of the Rallidae occur on every continent except [[Antarctica]]. Numerous island species are known. The most common rail habitats are [[marsh]]land and dense forest. They are especially fond of dense vegetation.<ref name=h&r2003-206-7>Horsfall & Robinson (2003): pp.&nbsp;206\u2013207</ref>\n\n==Name==\n\n\"Rail\" is derived from French ''r\u00e2le'', from Old French ''rasle''.  It is named from its harsh cry, in [[Vulgar Latin]] *''rascula'', from [[Latin]] ''r\u0101dere'' ('to scrape').<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=p-q6DAAAQBAJ&pg=PT132&dq=rasculum+rail#v=onepage|title=Lapwings, Loons and Lousy Jacks: The How and Why of Bird Names|first=Ray|last=Reedman|date=15 August 2016|publisher=Pelagic Publishing Ltd|isbn=9781784270933|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Morphology==\n[[File:Takahe.jpg|thumb|right|180px|South Island [[takahe]] (''Porphyrio hochstetteri'') from behind, showing the short, soft, and fluffy [[Flight feather|remiges]] typical of flightless rails]]\nThe rails are a family of small to medium-sized, ground-living birds. They vary in length from {{convert|12|to|63|cm|in|abbr=on}} and in weight from {{convert|20|to|3000|g|oz|abbr=on}}. Some species have long necks and in many cases are laterally compressed.\n\nThe [[beak|bill]] is the most variable feature within the family. In some species, it is longer than the head (like the [[clapper rail]] of [[the Americas]]); in others, it may be short and wide (as in the [[coot]]s), or massive (as in the [[Porphyrio|purple gallinules]]).<ref name=h&r2003-208>Horsfall & Robinson (2003): p. 208</ref> A few coots and gallinules have a [[frontal shield]], which is a fleshy, rearward extension of the upper bill. The most complex frontal shield is found in the [[horned coot]].<ref name=h&r2003-210>Horsfall & Robinson (2003): p. 210</ref>\n\nRails exhibit very little [[sexual dimorphism]] in either [[plumage]] or size.\n\n===Flight and flightlessness===\nThe wings of all rails are short and rounded. The [[bird flight|flight]] of those Rallidae able to fly, while not powerful, can be sustained for long periods of time, and many species [[bird migration|migrate]] annually. The weakness of their flight, however, means they are easily blown off course, thus are common [[Vagrancy (biology)|vagrants]], a characteristic that has led them to colonize many isolated oceanic islands. Furthermore, these birds often prefer to run rather than fly, especially in dense habitat. Some are also flightless at some time during their [[moult]] periods.<ref name=h&r2003-209>Horsfall & Robinson (2003): p. 209</ref>\n\nFlightlessness in rails is one of the best examples of [[parallel evolution]] in the animal kingdom. Of the roughly 150 historically known rail species, 31 extant or recently extinct species evolved flightlessness from volant (flying) ancestors.<ref>Kirchman (2012)</ref> This process created the endemic populations of flightless rails seen on Pacific islands today.\n\nMany island rails are flightless because small island habitats without mammalian predators eliminate the need to fly or move long distances. [[Bird flight|Flight]] makes intense demands, with the [[keel (bird)|keel]] and flight muscles taking up to a quarter of a bird's weight in flying Rallidae species. Reducing the flight muscles, with a corresponding lowering of [[metabolism|metabolic]] demands, reduces the flightless rail's energy expenditures.<ref>McNab & Ellis (2006)</ref> For this reason, flightlessness makes it easier to survive and colonize an island where resources may be limited.<ref name=\"McNab 1994\">McNab (1994)</ref> This also allows for the evolution of multiple sizes of flightless rails on the same island as the birds diversify to find niches.<ref>Trewick (1997)</ref>\n\nIn addition to energy conservation, certain morphological traits also affect rail evolution. Rails have relatively shortened wings to begin with, which in combination with their terrestrial habits and behavioral flightlessness, lends speed to the evolution of flightlessness, making it remarkably fast;<ref>Livezey 2003</ref> as few as 125,000 years were needed for the [[Laysan rail]] to lose the power of flight and evolve the reduced, stubby wings only useful to keep balance when running quickly.<ref>Slikas ''et al.'' (2002)</ref> Indeed, some argue that measuring the evolution of flightlessness in rails in generations rather than millennia might be possible.<ref name=\"McNab 1994\"/>\n\nAnother factor that contributes to the occurrence of the flightless state is a climate that does not necessitate seasonal long-distance migration; this is evidenced by the tendency to evolve flightlessness at a much greater occurrence in tropical islands than in temperate or polar islands.<ref name=\"McNab 2002\">McNab 2002</ref>\n[[File:American Coot skeleton.jpg|thumb|[[American coot]] (Fulica americana) skeleton on display at the [[Museum of Osteology]].]]\nIt is paradoxical, since rails appear loath to fly, that the evolution of flightless rails would necessitate high dispersal to isolated islands.<ref name=\"McNab and Ellis 2006\">McNab and Ellis 2006</ref> Nonetheless, three species of small-massed rails, ''[[buff-banded rail|Gallirallus philippensis]]'', ''[[purple swamphen|Porphyrio porphyrio]]'', and ''[[spotless crake|Porzana tabuensis]]'', exhibit a persistently high ability to disperse long distances among tropic Pacific islands,<ref name=\"McNab and Ellis 2006\"/> though only the latter two gave rise to flightless endemic species throughout the Pacific Basin.<ref name=\"Kirchman 2012\">Kirchman 2012</ref> In examining the phylogeny of ''G. philippensis'', although the species is clearly polyphyletic (it has more than one ancestral species), it is not the ancestor of most of its flightless descendants, revealing that the flightless condition evolved in rails before speciation was complete.<ref name=\"Kirchman 2012\"/>\n\nA consequence of lowered energy expenditure in flightless island rails has also been associated with evolution of their \"tolerance\" and \"approachability\".<ref name=\"McNab 2002\"/> For example, the (non-Rallidae) Corsican [[blue tit]]s exhibit lower aggression and reduced territorial defense behaviors than do their mainland European counterparts,<ref>Perret and Blondel 1993</ref> but this tolerance may be limited to close relatives.<ref>Granjon and Cheylan 1989</ref> The resulting kin-selecting altruistic phenomena reallocate resources to produce fewer young that are more competitive and would benefit the population as an entirety, rather than many young that would exhibit less fitness.<ref name=\"McNab 2002\"/> Unfortunately, with the human occupation of most islands in the past 5,000 to 35,000 years, selection has undoubtedly reversed the tolerance into a wariness of humans and predators, causing species unequipped for the change to become susceptible to extinction.<ref name=\"McNab 2002\"/>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\nIn general, members of the Rallidae are omnivorous generalists. Many species eat [[invertebrate]]s, as well as fruit or seedlings. A few species are primarily [[Herbivore|herbivorous]].<ref name=h&r2003-206-7 /> The [[bird song|calls]] of Rallidae species vary and are often quite loud. Some are whistle-like or squeak-like, while others seem unbirdlike.<ref name=\"Perrins p207\">Horsfall & Robinson (2003): p.&nbsp;207</ref> Loud calls are useful in dense vegetation, or at night where seeing another member of the species is difficult. Some calls are [[Territory (animal)|territorial]].<ref name=h&r2003-208 />\n\nThe most typical family members occupy dense [[vegetation]] in damp environments near [[lake]]s, [[swamp]]s, or [[river]]s. [[Reed bed]]s are a particularly favoured habitat. Those that [[bird migration|migrate]] do so at night.\n\nMost [[bird nest|nest]] in dense vegetation. In general, they are shy, secretive, and difficult to observe. Most species walk and run vigorously on strong legs, and have long toes that are well adapted to soft, uneven surfaces. They tend to have short, rounded wings, and although they are generally weak [[Bird flight|fliers]], they are, nevertheless, capable of covering long distances. Island species often become [[Flightless bird|flightless]], and many of them are now [[Extinction|extinct]] following the introduction of terrestrial [[Predation|predators]] such as [[cat]]s, [[rat]]s, and [[pig]]s.\n\nMany reedbed species are secretive (apart from loud calls), [[crepuscular]], and have laterally flattened bodies. In the [[Old World]], long-billed species tend to be called rails and short-billed species crakes. [[North America]]n species are normally called rails irrespective of bill length. The smallest of these is [[Swinhoe's rail]], at {{convert|13|cm|in|abbr=on}} and 25&nbsp;g. The larger species are also sometimes given other names. The black coots are more adapted to open water than their relatives, and some other large species are called gallinules and swamphens. The largest of this group is the [[takahe]], at {{convert|65|cm|in|abbr=on}} and {{convert|2.7|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe rails have suffered disproportionally from human changes to the environment, and an estimated<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Magnitude and variation of prehistoric bird extinctions in the Pacific|first1=Richard P.|last1=Duncan|first2=Alison G.|last2=Boyer|first3=Tim M.|last3=Blackburn|year=2013|journal=PNAS|volume=110|issue=16|pages=6436\u20136441|doi=10.1073/pnas.1216511110|pmid=23530197|pmc=3631643}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://therevelator.org/memorial-day-wake-island-rail/|title=Memorializing the Wake Island Rail: An Extinction Caused by War|last=Platt|first=John R.|date=May 2018|website=TheRevelator.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Extinction and Biogeography of Tropical Pacific Birds|last=Steadman|first=David W.|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2006|isbn=9780226771427|location=|pages=296}}</ref> several hundred species of island rails have become extinct because of this. Several island species of rails remain [[endangered species|endangered]], and [[bird conservation|conservation]] organisations and governments continue to work to prevent their extinction.\n\n===Reproduction===\nThe breeding behaviors of many Rallidae species are poorly understood or unknown. Most are thought to be [[Monogamy|monogamous]], although [[polygyny]] and [[polyandry]] have been reported.<ref name=h&r2003-209-10>Horsfall & Robinson (2003): pp.&nbsp;209\u2013210</ref> Most often, they lay five to 10 [[egg (biology)|eggs]]. [[Clutch (eggs)|Clutch]]es as small as one or as large as 15 eggs are known.<ref name=h&r2003-209-10 /> Egg clutches may not always hatch at the same time. Chicks become mobile after a few days. They often depend on their parents until fledging, which happens around 1 month old.<ref name=h&r2003-210 />\n\n==Rallidae and humans==\n[[File:GuamRail02.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Guam rail]] is an example of an island species that has been badly affected by [[introduced species]].]]\n\nSome larger, more abundant rails are [[hunting|hunted]] and their eggs collected for food.<ref name=h&r2003-211>Horsfall & Robinson (2003): p. 211</ref> The [[Wake Island rail]] was hunted to extinction by the starving Japanese garrison after the island was cut off from supply during [[World War II]].<ref>BLI (2007)</ref> At least two species, the [[common moorhen]] and the [[American purple gallinule]], have been considered [[Pest (organism)|pests]].<ref name=h&r2003-211 />\n\n===Threats and conservation===\nDue to their tendencies towards flightlessness, many island species have been unable to cope with introduced species. The most dramatic human-caused extinctions occurred in the [[Pacific Ocean]] as people colonised the islands of [[Melanesia]], [[Polynesia]], and [[Micronesia]], during which an estimated 750\u20131800 species of birds became extinct, half of which were rails.<ref>Steadman (2006)</ref> Some species that came close to extinction, such as the [[Lord Howe woodhen]], and the takahe, have made modest recoveries due to the efforts of conservation organisations. The [[Guam rail]] came perilously close to extinction when [[brown tree snake]]s were introduced to [[Guam]], but some of the last remaining individuals were taken into captivity and are breeding well, though attempts at reintroduction have met with mixed results.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/GUAM-BROWN-TREE-SNAKE-RESPONSIBLE-FOR-EXTINCTION-OF-5-SPECIES/4b735e75e7fe9b8d2ef464b66ecaaa0c?searchfilter=Compilations%2Furl%2FAnimal+Attacks%2F46|title=GUAM: BROWN TREE SNAKE RESPONSIBLE FOR EXTINCTION OF 5 SPECIES|last=|first=|date=February 1996|website=AP Archive|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://animals.sandiegozoo.org/animals/guam-rail|title=Guam Rail Gallirallus owstoni|last=|first=|date=|website=San Diego Zoo.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birdlife.org/worldwide/news/guam-bird-coming-back-extinction-wild|title=Is this Guam bird coming back from extinction in the wild?|last=Hurrell|first=Shaun|date=|website=BirdLife International.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Systematics and evolution==\nThe family Rallidae was introduced (as Rallia) by the French [[polymath]] [[Constantine Samuel Rafinesque]] in 1815.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Rafinesque | first=Constantine Samuel | author-link=Constantine Samuel Rafinesque | year=1815 | title=Analyse de la nature ou, Tableau de l'univers et des corps organis\u00e9s | publisher=Self-published | place=Palermo | language=French | page=70 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48310148 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Bock | first=Walter J. | year=1994 | title=History and Nomenclature of Avian Family-Group Names | series=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History | volume= Number 222 | publisher=American Museum of Natural History | place=New York | pages=136, 252 | hdl=2246/830 }}<!--Linked page allows download of the 48MB pdf--></ref>\nThe family has traditionally been grouped with two families of larger birds, the [[crane (bird)|cranes]] and [[bustard]]s, as well as several smaller families of usually \"primitive\" midsized amphibious birds, to make up the order [[Gruiformes]]. The alternative [[Sibley-Ahlquist taxonomy]], which has been widely accepted in America, raises the family to ordinal level as the Ralliformes. Given uncertainty about gruiform [[Clade|monophyly]], this may or may not be correct; it certainly seems more justified than most of the Sibley-Ahlquist proposals. However, such a group would probably also include the [[Heliornithidae]] (finfoots and sungrebes), an exclusively [[Tropics|tropical]] group that is somewhat [[convergent evolution|convergent]] with [[grebe]]s, and usually united with the rails in the Ralli.\n\n===Extant and recently extinct genera===\n[[File:Red-Legged Crake.jpg|thumb|right|[[Red-legged crake]], ''Rallina fasciata'']]\n[[File:Rallus aquaticus 1 (Marek Szczepanek).jpg|thumb|right|[[Water rail]], ''Rallus aquaticus'']]\n[[File:Porzana porzana 5 (Marek Szczepanek).jpg|thumb|right|Immature [[spotted crake]] (''Porzana porzana'')]]\nThe list maintained by [[Frank Gill (ornithologist)|Frank Gill]] and David Donsker on behalf of the [[International Ornithological Committee]] (IOC) contains 156 species divided into 41 genera.<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title=Flufftails, finfoots, rails, trumpeters, cranes, limpkin | work=World Bird List Version 9.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/flufftails/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=8 July 2019 }}</ref> For more detail, see [[List of rail species]].\n\n* ''Himantornis'' \u2013 [[Nkulengu rail]]\n* ''Canirallus'' \u2013 [[grey-throated rail]]\n* ''[[Coturnicops]]'' (3 species)\n* ''Micropygia'' \u2013 [[ocellated crake]]\n* ''[[Rallicula]]'' \u2013 forest rails (4 species)\n* ''[[Rallina]]'' (4 species)\n* ''Anurolimnas'' \u2013 [[chestnut-headed crake]]\n* ''[[Laterallus]]'' (11 species)\n* ''[[Nesoclopeus]]'' (1 living species, 1 recently extinct)\n* ''[[Gallirallus]]'' \u2013 Austropacific rails (including ''Tricholimnas''; 11 living species, four recently extinct)\n* ''Diaphorapteryx'' \u2013 [[Hawkins's rail]] (recently extinct)\n* ''[[Rallus]]'' \u2013 typical rails (14 species)\n* ''[[Lewinia]]'' (3 species)\n* ''[[Dryolimnas]]'' (1 living species, 1 recently extinct)\n* ''Aphanapteryx'' \u2013 [[red rail]] (recently extinct)\n* ''Erythromachus'' \u2013 [[Rodrigues rail]] (recently extinct)\n* ''[[Crex]]'' (2 species)\n* ''Rougetius'' \u2013 [[Rouget's rail]]\n* ''Aramidopsis'' \u2013 [[snoring rail]]\n* ''Mundia'' \u2013 [[Ascension crake]] (recently extinct)\n* ''Aphanocrex'' \u2013 [[Saint Helena Rail]] (recently extinct)\n* ''Atlantisia'' \u2013 [[Inaccessible Island rail]]\n* ''[[Aramides]]'' \u2013 wood rails (8 species)\n* ''Amaurolimnas'' \u2013 [[uniform crake]]\n* ''[[Gymnocrex]]'' (3 species)\n* ''[[Amaurornis]]'' \u2013 bush-hens (8 species)\n* ''[[Porzana]]'' \u2013 typical crakes (14 living species, 5 recently extinct)\n* ''Aenigmatolimnas'' \u2013 [[striped crake]]\n* ''Cyanolimnas'' \u2013 [[Zapata rail]]\n* ''[[Neocrex]]'' (2 species)\n* ''[[Pardirallus]]'' (3 species)\n* ''Eulabeornis'' \u2013 [[chestnut rail]]\n* ''Habroptila'' \u2013 [[invisible rail]]\n* ''Megacrex'' \u2013 [[New Guinea flightless rail]]\n* ''Gallicrex'' \u2013 [[watercock]]\n* ''[[Porphyrio]]'' \u2013 swamphens and purple gallinules (10 living species, 2 recently extinct)\n* ''[[Moorhen|Gallinula]]'' \u2013 typical gallinules (5 living species, 2 recently extinct)\n* ''Paragallinula'' \u2013 [[lesser moorhen]]\n* ''Porphyriops'' \u2013 [[spot-flanked gallinule]]\n* ''[[Tribonyx]]'' \u2013 nativehens (2 living species)\n* ''[[Coot|Fulica]]'' \u2013 coots (10 living species, one recently extinct)\n* ''[[Mustelirallus]]'' (three species)\n\nAdditionally, many prehistoric rails of extant genera are known only from [[fossil]] or subfossil remains, such as the [[Ibiza rail]] (''Rallus eivissensis''). These have not been listed here; see the genus accounts and the articles on [[Fossil birds#Gruiformes|fossil]] and [[Late Quaternary prehistoric birds#Gruiformes|Late Quaternary prehistoric birds]] for these species.<!-- INSUGEOCorrelGeol14:191 -->\n\n[[File:Aphanapteryx bonasia.JPG|thumb|right|[[Pieter van den Broecke]]'s 1617 drawing of the [[red rail]] of [[Mauritius]], ''Aphanapteryx bonasia'']]\n\n===Phylogeny===\nThe Rallidae based on the work by John Boyd:<ref name=\"Boyd\">{{cite web|last=Boyd|first=John|year=2007|title=''GRUAE I- Opisthocomiformes & Gruiformes'' |url=http://jboyd.net/Taxo/List7.html#gruiformes |accessdate= 30 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|style=font-size:80%;line-height:80%\n|1={{clade\n  |1=?''[[Rougetius]]''\n  |label2=[[Rallinae]]\n  |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Anurolimnas]]''\n    |2={{clade\n      |1=?''[[Biensis]]''\n      |2=''[[Rallus]]''\n      |3={{clade\n        |1={{clade\n          |1=?''[[Gymnocrex]]''\n          |2=''[[Gallirallus]]''\n           }}\n        |2={{clade\n          |1=?\u2020''[[Aphanapteryx]]''\n          |2=?\u2020''[[Erythromachus]]''\n          |3={{clade\n            |1=''[[Dryolimnas]]''\n            |2={{clade\n              |1=''[[Crex]]''\n              |2=''[[Lewinia]]''\n               }}\n             }}\n           }}\n         }}\n       }}\n     }}\n  |3={{clade\n    |label1=[[Gallinulinae]]\n    |1={{clade\n      |label1=[[Pardirallini]]\n      |1={{clade\n        |1={{clade\n          |1=''[[Pardirallus]]''\n          |2=''[[Mustelirallus]]''\n           }}\n        |2={{clade\n          |1=''[[Amaurolimnas]]''\n          |2=''[[Aramides]]''\n           }}\n         }}\n      |label2=[[Gallinulini]]\n      |2={{clade\n        |1=?''[[Pareudiastes]]''\n        |2={{clade\n          |1={{clade\n            |1=''[[Tribonyx]]''\n            |2=''[[Porzana]]''\n             }}\n          |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Paragallinula]]''\n            |2={{clade\n              |1=''[[Gallinula]]''\n              |2=''[[Common moorhen|Fulica]]''\n               }}\n             }}\n           }}\n         }}\n       }}\n    |label2=[[Porphyrioninae]]\n    |2={{clade\n      |label1=[[Porphyrionini]]\n      |1={{clade\n        |1=\u2020''[[Aphanocrex]]''\n        |2=''[[Porphyrio]]''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n        |label1=[[Himantornithini]]\n        |1={{clade\n          |1={{clade\n            |1=''[[Himantornis]]''\n            |2=''[[Megacrex]]''\n             }}\n          |2={{clade\n            |1={{clade\n              |1=''[[Aenigmatolimnas]]''\n              |2=''[[Poliolimnas]]''\n               }}\n            |2={{clade\n              |1=''[[Gallicrex]]''\n              |2=''[[Amaurornis]]''\n               }}\n             }}\n           }}\n        |2={{clade\n          |label1=[[Zaporniini]]\n          |1={{clade\n            |1=''[[Rallina]]''\n            |2=''[[Zapornia]]''\n             }}\n          |label2=[[Laterallini]]\n          |2={{clade\n            |1={{clade\n              |1=''[[Micropygia]]''\n              |2=''[[Rufirallus]]''\n               }}\n            |2={{clade\n              |1=''[[Laterallus]]''\n              |2={{clade\n                |1={{clade\n                  |1=?''[[Ascension crake|Mundia]]''\n                  |2=''[[Creciscus]]''\n                   }}\n                |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Coturnicops]]''\n                  |2={{clade\n                    |1=''[[Hapalocrex]]''\n                    |2=''[[Limnocrex]]''\n                     }}\n                   }}\n                 }}\n               }}\n             }}\n           }}\n         }}\n       }}\n     }}\n   }}\n}}\n\n===Recently extinct genera===\n[[File:Rail, from the Game Birds series (N40) for Allen & Ginter Cigarettes MET DP839177.jpg|thumb|1888 color lithograph of a rail]]\n\n*Genus ''[[Nesotrochis]]'' \u2013 cave-rails (3 species; [[Extinction|extinct]] prehistoric)\n** [[Antillean cave rail]], ''Nesotrochis debooyi'' (Puerto Rico and Virgin Islands, West Indies) \u2013 prehistoric\n** Haitian cave-rail, ''Nesotrochis steganinos'' (Haiti, West Indies) \u2013 prehistoric\n** Cuban cave-rail, ''Nesotrochis picapicensis'' (Cuba, West Indies) \u2013 prehistoric\n*Genus ''Diaphorapteryx'' \u2013 [[Hawkins's rail]] (extinct 19th century)\n*Genus ''Aphanapteryx'' \u2013 [[Red rail]] (extinct mid-18th century)\n*Genus ''Erythromachus'' \u2013 [[Rodrigues rail]] (extinct mid-18th century)\n*Genus ''Cabalus'' \u2013 [[Chatham rail]] (sometimes included in ''Gallirallus''; extinct around 1900)\n*Genus ''Mundia'' \u2013 [[Ascension crake]] \u2013 formerly included in ''Atlantisia''; (late 17th century)\n*Genus ''Aphanocrex'' \u2013 [[Saint Helena swamphen]] (formerly included in ''Atlantisia''; extinct 16th century)\n\nThe undescribed Fernando de Noronha rail, genus and species undetermined, survived to historic times.<!-- AmMusNovit3256 -->\n\n===Late Quaternary prehistoric extinctions===\n*Genus ''Capellirallus'' \u2013 [[Snipe-rail]]\n*Genus ''Vitirallus'' \u2013 [[Viti Levu rail]].\n*Genus ''Hovacrex'' \u2013 [[Hova gallinule]]\nand see genus accounts\n\n===Fossil record===\n[[Fossil]] species of long-[[extinct]] [[prehistoric]] rails are richly documented from the well-researched [[formation (geology)|formations]] of [[Europe]]<ref>Ml\u00edkovsk\u00fd (2002)</ref> and [[North America]], as well from the less comprehensively studied strata elsewhere:\n\n*Genus ''Eocrex'' (Wasatch Early Eocene of Steamboat Springs, USA; Late Eocene \u2013 ?Oligocene of Isfara, Tadzhikistan)<!-- BullAMNH151:1; Condor33:107 --><!-- RussOrnitholJ135:199-201 -->\n*Genus ''Palaeorallus'' (Wasatch Early Eocene of Wyoming, USA)<!-- BullAMNH151:1; Condor33:107 -->\n*Genus ''Parvirallus'' (Early \u2013 Middle Eocene of England)\n*Genus ''Aletornis'' (Bridger Middle Eocene of Uinta County, USA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/12826/VZ_77_Synopsis_fossil_Rallidae.pdf|title=A SYNOPSIS OF THE FOSSIL RALLIDAE|last=OLSON|first=STORRS L.|date=1977|website=Smithsonian Libraries - Smithsonian Research Online|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref> \u2013 includes ''Protogrus''<!--  BullAMNH151:1; Condor44:126;Condor46:25;Condor54:174 https://books.google.com/books?id=mtNVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA32 appears to show this genus shouldn't be included-->\n*Genus ''Fulicaletornis'' (Bridger Middle Eocene of Henry's Fork, USA)<!-- BullAMNH151:1; Condor54:174 -->\n*Genus ''Latipons'' (Middle Eocene of Lee-on-Solent, England)\n*Genus ''Ibidopsis'' (Hordwell Late Eocene of Hordwell, UK)<!-- Ardea94:23; BullAMNH151:1-->\n*Genus ''Quercyrallus'' (Late Eocene -? Late Oligocene of France)<!-- Ardea94:23; BullAMNH151:1; Condor54:174 -->\n*Genus ''Belgirallus'' (Early Oligocene of WC Europe)<!-- Ardea94:23 -->\n*Genus ''Rallicrex'' (Corbula Middle/Late Oligocene of Kolzsv\u00e1r, Romania)<!-- BullAMNH151:1; Condor54:174 -->\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. (Late Oligocene of Billy-Cr\u00e9chy, France)<ref>A small species of rail: Hugueney ''et al.'' (2003)</ref>\n*Genus ''Palaeoaramides'' (Late Oligocene/Early Miocene \u2013 Late Miocene of France)<!-- Ardea94:23. BullAMNH151:1. Condor54:174. Geobios2:157. -->\n*Genus ''[[Rhenanorallus]]'' (Late Oligocene/Early Miocene of Mainz Basin, Germany)\n*Genus ''Paraortygometra'' (Late Oligocene/?Early Miocene -? Middle Miocene of France) \u2013 includes ''Microrallus''<!-- BullAMNH151:1. Condor54:174. Geobios2:157;36:719. -->\n*Genus ''[[Australlus]]'' (Late Oligocene \u2013 Middle Miocene of NW Queensland, Australia)\n*Genus ''Pararallus'' (Late Oligocene? \u2013 Late Miocene of C Europe) \u2013 possibly belongs in ''Palaeoaramides''<!-- BullAMNH151:1; Condor54:174 -->\n*Genus ''Litorallus'' (Early Miocene of New Zealand)\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. (Bathans Early/Middle Miocene of Otago, New Zealand)<ref>Dozens of mostly broken isolated skull and limb bones of a rail or crake the size of a [[slaty-breasted rail|slaty-breasted]] or small [[buff-banded rail]]: Worthy ''et al.'' (2007)</ref>\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. (Bathans Early/Middle Miocene of Otago, New Zealand)<ref>[[Quadrate (bone)|Quadrate]] ([[Museum of New Zealand|MNZ]] S.40957) and 2 [[femur|femora]] (MNZ S.42658, S.42785) of a rail or crake the size of a large [[buff-banded rail]]: Worthy ''et al.'' (2007)</ref>\n*Genus ''Miofulica'' (Anversian Black Sand Middle Miocene of Antwerp, Belgium)<!-- BullAMNH151:1; Condor54:174 -->\n*Genus ''Miorallus'' (Middle Miocene of Sansan, France -? Late Miocene of Rudab\u00e1nya, Hungary)<!-- BullAMNH151:1; Condor54:174; PaleontogrItal89:3 -->\n*Genus ''Youngornis'' (Shanwang Middle Miocene of Linqu, China)\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. (Saj\u00f3v\u00f6lgyi Middle Miocene of M\u00e1trasz\u00f5l\u00f5s, Hungary)<ref>Several limb bones of a smallish rail: G\u00e1l ''et al.'' (1998\u201399)</ref>\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. (Middle Miocene of Grive-Saint-Alban, France)<ref>Partial hand of a [[common moorhen]]-sized rail: Ballmann (1969)</ref>\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. (Late Miocene of Lemoyne Quarry, USA)\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. UMMP V55013-55014; UMMP V55012/V45750/V45746 (Rexroad Late Pliocene of Saw Rock Canyon, USA)\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. UMMP V29080 (Rexroad Late Pliocene of Fox Canyon, USA)\n*Genus ''Creccoides'' (Blanco Late Pliocene/Early Pleistocene of Crosby County, USA)<!-- *ProcAmPhilosSoc030:123 -->\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. (Bermuda, West Atlantic)\n*Rallidae gen. et sp. indet. (formerly ''[[Barbados rail|Fulica podagrica]]'') (Late Pleistocene of Barbados)<ref>Olson, Storrs L. (1974). \"A new species of Nesotrochis from Hispaniola, with notes on other fossil rails from the West Indies (Aves: Rallidae)\". ''Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington''. '''87'''(38): 439\u2013450. {{hdl|10088/8374}}.</ref>\n*Genus ''[[Pleistorallus]]'' (mid-Pleistocene New Zealand).<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Worthy | first1 = T.H. | year = 1997 | title = A mid-Pleistocene rail from New Zealand | url = | journal = Alcheringa: An Australasian Journal of Palaeontology | volume = 21 | issue = 1| pages = 71\u201378 | doi = 10.1080/03115519708619186 }}</ref> The [[holotype]] of ''Pleistorallus flemingi'' is in the collection of the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Pleistorallus flemingi; holotype | work = Collections Online | publisher = Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa | url = http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/ObjectDetails.aspx?oid=389388 | accessdate = 18 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Doubtfully placed here===\nThese taxa may or may not have been rails:\n* Genus ''[[Ludiortyx]]'' (Late Eocene) \u2013 includes ''\"Tringa\" hoffmanni'', ''\"Palaeortyx\" blanchardi'', ''\"P.\" hoffmanni''\n* Genus ''Telecrex'' (Irdin Manha Late Eocene of Chimney Butte, China)<!-- AmMusNovit711. BullAMNH151:1. -->\n* Genus ''[[Amitabha (bird)|Amitabha]]'' (Bridger middle Eocene of Forbidden City, USA) \u2013 phasianid?\n* Genus ''Palaeocrex'' (Early Oligocene of Trigonias Quarry, USA)<!-- BullAMNH151:1-->\n* Genus ''Rupelrallus'' (Early Oligocene of Germany)\n* Neornithes incerta sedis (Late Oligocene of Riversleigh, Australia)<ref>Specimen [[Queensland Museum|QM F40203]]. A left [[carpometacarpus]] piece of a bird about the size of [[Lewin's rail]]. Probably from a rail, but it is too damaged to determine its affiliations more precisely: Boles (2005)</ref>\n* Genus ''Euryonotus'' (Pleistocene of Argentina)<!-- Evolution39:1174 -->\n\nThe presumed scolopacid [[wader]] ''Limosa gypsorum'' (Montmartre Late Eocene of France) is sometimes considered a rail and then placed in the genus ''Montirallus''.<ref>Olson (1985), Ml\u00edkovsk\u00fd (2002)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{portal-inline|Animals}}\n* {{portal-inline|Birds}}\n* {{portal-inline|Biology}}\n* [[List of Gruiformes by population]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Ballmann | first1 = Peter | year = 1969 | title = Les Oiseaux mioc\u00e8nes de la Grive-Saint-Alban (Is\u00e8re) [The Miocene birds of Grive-Saint-Alban (Is\u00e8re)]. | url = | journal = [[Geobios]] | volume = 2 | issue = | pages = 157\u2013204 | doi = 10.1016/S0016-6995(69)80005-7 }}\n* [[BirdLife International]] (BLI) (2007): [http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=2858&m=0 Wake Island Rail BirdLife Species Factsheet]. Retrieved 2007-07-04.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Boles | first1 = Walter E | year = 2005 | title = A New Flightless Gallinule (Aves: Rallidae: ''Gallinula'') from the Oligo-Miocene of Riversleigh, Northwestern Queenslan